I've been looking at ChatGPT and seeing what it knows about Antlr. This kind of surprised me.

	ChatGPT, please give me an Antlr grammar for integer expressions.

	Certainly! Here's an Antlr grammar for integer expressions:

	grammar IntegerExpressions;

	/* Lexer rules */
	INT: [0-9]+;
	PLUS: '+';
	MINUS: '-';
	MULT: '*';
	DIV: '/';

	/* Parser rules */
	expression: term ((PLUS | MINUS) term)*;
	term: factor ((MULT | DIV) factor)*;
	factor: INT | '(' expression ')';

	/* Ignored characters */
	WS: [ \t\r\n]+ -> skip;

	Here, we define the tokens for integers, plus, minus, multiplication, and division. We then define the parser rules for expressions, terms, and factors. An expression is defined as one or more terms separated by plus or minus signs, a term is defined as one or more factors separated by multiplication or division signs, and a factor is either an integer or an expression enclosed in parentheses. We also define the WS rule to ignore whitespace characters.

	You can then generate a parser for this grammar in your target language using the Antlr tool.

